    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-12-31T17:34:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-05-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="292" subtype="editorial-note"
                type="document" xml:id="d292">
                <head>No. 292<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>Despatch 359 from Jidda, May 30, transmitted to the Department of State an
                    account of two meetings held on May 21 and May 23 between <gloss
                        target="#t_Aramco1">Aramco</gloss> representatives and a Saudi Arabian group
                    headed by Prince <persName corresp="#p_IAAF1">Faisal</persName>. At a short
                    meeting on May 21, Prince <persName corresp="#p_IAAF1">Faisal</persName> handed
                    the <gloss target="#t_Aramco1">Aramco</gloss> representatives a memorandum which
                    stated the specific demands of the Saudi Arabian Government regarding oil
                    pricing. On May 23, <gloss target="#t_Aramco1">Aramco</gloss> representatives
                    stated they could not accept the Saudi Arabian memorandum, and agreement was
                    reached to reconvene the negotiations after Ramadan. (886A.2553/5–3053) Despatch
                    393, June 27, reported to the Department of State that <gloss
                        target="#t_Aramco1">Aramco</gloss> representatives had brought to the
                    Embassy’s attention a number of measures recently adopted by the <pb facs="0707"
                        n="667" xml:id="pg_667"/> Saudi Arabian Government which they considered
                    clearly planned to force <gloss target="#t_Aramco1">Aramco</gloss> to agree to
                    the government’s pricing proposals. (886A.2553/6–2753)</p>
            </div>
